---

<Layout title="Tachyons - Docs">
  <Header />
  <div class='p4'>
    <h2>Background Size</h2>
    <p class='lh-body measure'>
      Background-size affects how background images fill their containing elements. While measurements can be declared explicitly to size an image, the values that seem most reusable are contain and cover. 
    </p>
  </div>
  <section class='p4'>
    <h3>Values</h3>
<code class='pre db mb5'>.cover   &#123; background-size: cover!important; &#125;
.contain &#123; background-size: contain!important; &#125;
.bg1     &#123; background-size: 16px; &#125;
.bg2     &#123; background-size: 32px; &#125;
.bg3     &#123; background-size: 64px; &#125;
.bg4     &#123; background-size: 128px; &#125;
.bg-100  &#123; background-size: 100%; &#125;
.bg-150  &#123; background-size: 150%; &#125;
.bg-200  &#123; background-size: 200%; &#125;
</code>
  </section>
  <section class='p4'>
    <h3>Examples</h3>
        <div>
          <code class="fw4 dib">.contain &#123; background-size: contain &#125;</code>
          <p class="measure lh-copy mt3"><code>contain</code> will make sure that the entire image is displayed within the element, regardless of the elements dimensions.</p>
          <div style="background-image: url(http://placekitten.com/g/500/500);background-repeat: no-repeat;outline: 1px solid black;" class="contain h4 w-100">
          </div>
        </div>
        <div>
          <code class="fw4 dib">.cover &#123; background-size: cover &#125;</code>
          <p class="measure lh-copy mt3"><code>cover</code> will make sure the entire element is covered - but wonâ€™t guarantee that the entire image will be shown.</p>
          <div style="background-image: url(http://placekitten.com/g/500/500); outline: 1px solid black;" class="cover h4 w-100">
          </div>
        </div>
  </section>
  <section class='p4'>
    <h3>Reference</h3>
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/font-size">MDN - font-size</a>
  </section> 
  <Footer />
</Layout>

